erosions, fissures and scars thrown in there.

35
00:02:00.120 --> 00:02:03.360
And we're gonna go throw a lot of this stuff on warp speed

36
00:02:03.360 --> 00:02:05.103
and we'll finish within the hour.

37
00:02:06.390 --> 00:02:10.110
When you see a question in dermatology on the boards,

38
00:02:10.110 --> 00:02:12.900
they tend to come in one of two ways,

39
00:02:12.900 --> 00:02:17.400
questions with pictures and questions without pictures,

40
00:02:17.400 --> 00:02:21.330
and we'll see both of those to help you today.

41
00:02:21.330 --> 00:02:22.680
Now COVID is with us

42
00:02:22.680 --> 00:02:26.253
and there's actually dermatologic issues related to COVID.

43
00:02:27.390 --> 00:02:29.760
Almost 20% of some patients COVID

44
00:02:29.760 --> 00:02:32.580
will have dermatologic findings

45
00:02:32.580 --> 00:02:37.140
and most common are the maculopapular/morbilifirm rashes,

46
00:02:37.140 --> 00:02:39.750
followed by the COVID toes,

47
00:02:39.750 --> 00:02:44.750
what they call pseudochilbain or pernio-like acral lesions.

48
00:02:45.630 --> 00:02:47.400
And here we have some pictures of those

49
00:02:47.400 --> 00:02:49.503
with pernio sitting there on the left.

50
00:02:50.610 --> 00:02:53.670
The reticular form lesions were more purpuric,

51
00:02:53.670 --> 00:02:57.903
those occur more in your sicker patients in the ICU setting.

52
00:02:59.910 --> 00:03:02.943
Our first question for you, case number one.

53
00:03:04.140 --> 00:03:07.830
45-year-old male presents with a chronic rash present

54
00:03:07.830 --> 00:03:10.443
over his knees and his elbows.

55
00:03:13.260 --> 00:03:14.790
Which of the following represents

56
00:03:14.790 --> 00:03:17.310
the most likely diagnosis here?

57
00:03:17.310 --> 00:03:20.850
Is it Tinea corporis, psoriasis,

58
00:03:20.850 --> 00:03:24.003
mycosis fungoides or Bowen's disease?

59
00:03:29.610 --> 00:03:31.588
Oh, look at this.

60
00:03:31.588 --> 00:03:34.830
(attendees applauding)

61
00:03:34.830 --> 00:03:37.740
Yep, our patient has psoriasis, very good.

62
00:03:37.740 --> 00:03:40.590
This is a plaque and scale-like disease,

63
00:03:40.590 --> 00:03:44.460
psoriasis, chronic lupus, tinea corporis,

64
00:03:44.460 --> 00:03:47.970
Paget's disease, lichen planus, Bowen's disease,

65
00:03:47.970 --> 00:03:52.020
cutaneous T-cell lymphomas, Pityriasis rosea,

66
00:03:52.020 --> 00:03:54.900
syphilis, ichthyosis, a number of things

67
00:03:54.900 --> 00:03:57.930
that present with plaques and scales.

68
00:03:57.930 --> 00:04:00.300
Here we have tinea corporis,

69
00:04:00.300 --> 00:04:04.863
a well-defined border with central clearing.

70
00:04:05.780 --> 00:04:09.330
Pityriasis rosea scale-like lesions here.

71
00:04:09.330 --> 00:04:12.540
If you're lucky to see the herald patch,

72
00:04:12.540 --> 00:04:16.830
that may be the beginning of that disease process for you.

73
00:04:16.830 --> 00:04:21.153
Bowen's disease, precursor for squamous cell carcinoma.

74
00:04:22.350 --> 00:04:25.350
Ichthyosis, fish scale-like skin,

75
00:04:25.350 --> 00:04:29.130
tends to be hereditary and all over the body.

76
00:04:29.130 --> 00:04:31.380
We had some inter-practice with this.

77
00:04:31.380 --> 00:04:36.300
Lichen planus there's a vivacious plaque-like lesions there.

78
00:04:36.300 --> 00:04:38.220
Lichen simplex chronicus,

79
00:04:38.220 --> 00:04:40.800
itches a lot, scratches a lot.

80
00:04:40.800 --> 00:04:44.310
Some people just scratch and they get neural dermatitis

81
00:04:44.310 --> 00:04:45.660
and they get plaques and scales

82
00:04:45.660 --> 00:04:48.360
at the site of their excoriations.

83
00:04:48.360 --> 00:04:52.830
But our patient has psoriasis, typical psoriasis.

84
00:04:52.830 --> 00:04:55.890
Oval, erythematous, plaque-like lesions

85
00:04:55.890 --> 00:04:57.810
often at the site of trauma.

86
00:04:57.810 --> 00:05:01.080
Look for them on extensor surfaces, elbows,

87
00:05:01.080 --> 00:05:03.093
knees, scalp.

88
00:05:04.020 --> 00:05:07.320
Patients can get systematically sick with psoriasis.

89
00:05:07.320 --> 00:05:10.830
With arthritis, often they'll have pitting fingernails

90
00:05:10.830 --> 00:05:13.203
as a clue that it's psoriatic arthritis.

91
00:05:14.100 --> 00:05:15.780
Chronic plaque-like psoriasis,

92
00:05:15.780 --> 00:05:17.940
the most common thing we're gonna see,

93
00:05:17.940 --> 00:05:19.503
but there are others as well.

94
00:05:21.180 --> 00:05:22.500
How do you treat it?

95
00:05:22.500 --> 00:05:24.150
When there's not a lot of involvement,

96
00:05:24.150 --> 00:05:26.130
we use topical steroids.

97
00:05:26.130 --> 00:05:29.610
Calcipotriene which is a vitamin D analog.

98
00:05:29.610 --> 00:05:31.590
Calcitriol, another analog.

99
00:05:31.590 --> 00:05:35.220
Calcineurin inhibitors like tacrolimus.

100
00:05:35.220 --> 00:05:37.290
Tazarotene, been around for a while.

101
00:05:37.290 --> 00:05:42.290
Coal tars, even aspirin and phototherapy.

102
00:05:43.080 --> 00:05:45.690
But when it becomes more involved,

103
00:05:45.690 --> 00:05:48.120
that's more the purview of the dermatologist,

104
00:05:48.120 --> 00:05:50.643
they use different kind of light therapies.

105
00:05:52.650 --> 00:05:54.900
And if there's systemic involvement,

106
00:05:54.900 --> 00:05:57.660
disease modifying agents similar to what you might use

107
00:05:57.660 --> 00:06:01.860
for rheumatoid arthritis and any one of those biologics

108
00:06:01.860 --> 00:06:05.970
or anti-TNF agents that you see advertised on TV

109
00:06:05.970 --> 00:06:09.393
without ever a price tag because they're super expensive.

110
00:06:11.280 --> 00:06:14.733
Number two, can you see this lady?

111
00:06:16.680 --> 00:06:19.260
Okay, there she is again.

112
00:06:19.260 --> 00:06:24.260
65-year-old lady presents with this painful rash

113
00:06:24.270 --> 00:06:26.733
on one side of her face.

114
00:06:30.150 --> 00:06:32.460
Which of the following therapeutic modalities

115
00:06:32.460 --> 00:06:35.400
would be most beneficial in the initial stage

116
00:06:35.400 --> 00:06:37.020
of this illness?

117
00:06:37.020 --> 00:06:41.730
Prednisone, valacyclovir, silver sulfadiazine

118
00:06:41.730 --> 00:06:42.963
or gabapentin?

119
00:06:47.940 --> 00:06:50.220
And you're gonna work with Valtrex, good.

120
00:06:50.220 --> 00:06:52.293
Why? What's wrong with this patient?

121
00:06:54.180 --> 00:06:56.733
Herpes zoster, got shingles, right?

122
00:06:57.660 --> 00:06:59.100
These are bullous lesions.

123
00:06:59.100 --> 00:07:03.150
They start off that way, herpes simplex, herpes zoster,

124
00:07:03.150 --> 00:07:06.150
bullous impetigo, dermatitis herpetiformis,

125
00:07:06.150 --> 00:07:08.683
second degree burns, bullous pemphigoid,

126
00:07:08.683 --> 00:07:11.553
pemphigus vulgaris, to name a few.

127
00:07:12.420 --> 00:07:14.670
This is bullous pemphigoid.

128
00:07:14.670 --> 00:07:16.503
These bullied tend to be tense,

129
00:07:17.700 --> 00:07:20.730
non-painful often the elderly.

130
00:07:20.730 --> 00:07:24.450
If you push on it, they don't spread.

131
00:07:24.450 --> 00:07:26.340
If you push on it and they spread

132
00:07:26.340 --> 00:07:30.120
and the tissue comes off, that's called Nikolsky's sign.

133
00:07:30.120 --> 00:07:31.677
That's pemphigus vulgaris

134
00:07:31.677 --> 00:07:33.753
and that's bad news for your patient.

135
00:07:34.590 --> 00:07:37.860
Second-degree burns blister, first-degree sunburn,

136
00:07:37.860 --> 00:07:40.710
third-degree ulceration.

137
00:07:40.710 --> 00:07:45.710
Dr. Dash made me reiterate the fact

138
00:07:45.930 --> 00:07:50.930
that we don't treat this with silver sulfadiazine anymore.

139
00:07:51.840 --> 00:07:55.260
We don't use that for a second-degree burns.

140
00:07:55.260 --> 00:07:57.393
Silvadene's no longer what we use.

141
00:07:58.380 --> 00:08:02.460
Erythema multiforme, typically are target lesions,

142
00:08:02.460 --> 00:08:05.163
but they can blister emboli as well.

143
00:08:06.930 --> 00:08:09.480
Our patient has zoster or shingles

144
00:08:09.480 --> 00:08:13.140
or reactivation of the Varicella-zoster virus,

145
00:08:13.140 --> 00:08:16.623
usually involving a single dermatome, but occasionally more.

146
00:08:17.670 --> 00:08:19.230
Before you see the rash,

147
00:08:19.230 --> 00:08:22.560
there's often burning and fever and itching

148
00:08:22.560 --> 00:08:25.890
and if you can diagnose zoster before the rash occurs,

149
00:08:25.890 --> 00:08:27.240
then your reputation is great

150
00:08:27.240 --> 00:08:29.913
and your community for years and years to come.

151
00:08:31.110 --> 00:08:35.310
Look for vesicles, varying size at a red base.

152
00:08:35.310 --> 00:08:38.973
They come in crops, they crust over in about 2 to 3 weeks.

153
00:08:40.050 --> 00:08:43.560
And you may see postherpetic neuralgia more often

154
00:08:43.560 --> 00:08:46.920
in the elderly and more often if there is significant pain

155
00:08:46.920 --> 00:08:49.110
during the rash itself.

156
00:08:49.110 --> 00:08:54.060
If the rash all comes at the same time all over the patient,

157
00:08:54.060 --> 00:08:56.370
then notify homeland security.

158
00:08:56.370 --> 00:08:59.160
That may be the first case of smallpox

159
00:08:59.160 --> 00:09:00.423
that you have ever seen.

160
00:09:01.410 --> 00:09:03.360
How do we treat herpes zoster?

161
00:09:03.360 --> 00:09:06.690
Analgesics, things like wet compressors

162
00:09:06.690 --> 00:09:11.190
and the big three antivirals choose amongst acyclovir,

163
00:09:11.190 --> 00:09:13.980
famciclovir or valacyclovir.

164
00:09:13.980 --> 00:09:17.580
It doses higher to a Dr. Weismiller will tell you later,

165
00:09:17.580 --> 00:09:19.083
treat genital herpes.

166
00:09:20.820 --> 00:09:21.840
What about steroids?

167
00:09:21.840 --> 00:09:24.600
Prednisone, they may decrease pain initially,

168
00:09:24.600 --> 00:09:27.090
but may increase the likelihood

169
00:09:27.090 --> 00:09:29.250
of a secondary bacterial infection.

170
00:09:29.250 --> 00:09:31.980
We used them more in the past than we do now

171
00:09:31.980 --> 00:09:34.383
and they don't decrease postherpetic neuralgia.

172
00:09:35.340 --> 00:09:37.410
If you get postherpetic neuralgia,

173
00:09:37.410 --> 00:09:39.480
treatment modality similar we talked about

174
00:09:39.480 --> 00:09:41.610
in the pain lecture earlier,

175
00:09:41.610 --> 00:09:45.600
anti-convulsants, tricyclics, opioids,

176
00:09:45.600 --> 00:09:46.893
even nerve blocks.

177
00:09:49.290 --> 00:09:53.100
We now have a vaccine to prevent this.

178
00:09:53.100 --> 00:09:55.770
Shingrix, which replaced Zostavax,

179
00:09:55.770 --> 00:09:57.990
which is not quite as effective.

180
00:09:57.990 --> 00:10:02.310
Shingrix is a recombinant vaccine given in two doses

181
00:10:02.310 --> 00:10:06.360
for patients over the age of 50, 90% effective.

182
00:10:06.360 --> 00:10:09.540
You can give this if they've had shingles before.

183
00:10:09.540 --> 00:10:12.450
If they have shingles now, wait for all the lesions

184
00:10:12.450 --> 00:10:16.320
to fully heal before you consider giving this.

185
00:10:16.320 --> 00:10:19.620
Is not for people who are pregnant or breastfeeding.

186
00:10:19.620 --> 00:10:20.733
Case number three.

187
00:10:22.440 --> 00:10:24.240
Look at the hand.

188
00:10:24.240 --> 00:10:28.050
25-year-old male, known HIV infection lives

189
00:10:28.050 --> 00:10:31.590
in substandard housing as we provide for our residents

190
00:10:31.590 --> 00:10:35.643
and students and presents with a generalized pruritic rash.

191
00:10:39.330 --> 00:10:41.550
Which of the following represents the best treatment

192
00:10:41.550 --> 00:10:42.930
for this condition?

193
00:10:42.930 --> 00:10:47.930
Is it prednisone, hydroxyzine, permethrin 5% or abacavir?

194
00:10:54.750 --> 00:10:57.720
Oh, we're three for three, Permethrin.

195
00:10:57.720 --> 00:10:59.373
Why? What's wrong with this guy?

196
00:11:00.390 --> 00:11:02.310
He's got scabies.

197
00:11:02.310 --> 00:11:03.303
He sure does.

198
00:11:04.470 --> 00:11:07.920
These are erythematous and pruritic,

199
00:11:07.920 --> 00:11:11.610
these are papules, miliaria,

200
00:11:11.610 --> 00:11:15.450
atopic dermatitis, urticaria, may look papular,

201
00:11:15.450 --> 00:11:19.440
insect bites, scabies, the eruption of HIV,

202
00:11:19.440 --> 00:11:22.743
the pruritic papules and plaques of pregnancy.

203
00:11:24.930 --> 00:11:27.453
Here's a patient with atopic dermatitis.

204
00:11:28.590 --> 00:11:31.500
Notice involvement the flexor surface

205
00:11:31.500 --> 00:11:33.120
and the cubital fossa as opposed

206
00:11:33.120 --> 00:11:37.020
to psoriasis on extensor surfaces.

207
00:11:37.020 --> 00:11:40.530
Urticaria looking kind of papular here.

208
00:11:40.530 --> 00:11:43.720
We all know why you never give Benadryl to a bee

209
00:11:45.090 --> 00:11:46.923
because it'll ruin their hives.

210
00:11:48.060 --> 00:11:50.793
Scabies as we see in our patients.

211
00:11:52.080 --> 00:11:55.170
Hypersensitivity reaction to the mighty mite,

212
00:11:55.170 --> 00:11:58.080
Sarcoptes scabiei.

213
00:11:58.080 --> 00:12:00.450
We don't provide it with indoor plumbing,

214
00:12:00.450 --> 00:12:04.830
so as it lays and moves around their surface of their skin,

215
00:12:04.830 --> 00:12:07.960
it lays eggs and fecal pellets, which you call scybala

216
00:12:08.850 --> 00:12:11.310
and those cause a reaction.

217
00:12:11.310 --> 00:12:14.190
The board's not gonna ask you about scybala.

218
00:12:14.190 --> 00:12:17.700
The mites like to move at night, so things itch more than.

219
00:12:17.700 --> 00:12:19.803
You can find the burrows if you're lucky.

220
00:12:21.420 --> 00:12:22.650
Where do you look for them?

221
00:12:22.650 --> 00:12:25.770
Finger webs often or anywhere in the body

222
00:12:25.770 --> 00:12:28.830
and the genital region in adults.

223
00:12:28.830 --> 00:12:32.100
And here's a scabies, couple scabies burrows.

224
00:12:32.100 --> 00:12:34.980
If you're finding a hard time being sure that they're there,

225
00:12:34.980 --> 00:12:37.170
what you do is take a felt pen

226
00:12:37.170 --> 00:12:40.080
and you go ahead and color over the burrow,

227
00:12:40.080 --> 00:12:41.490
and the ink gets into the burrow,

228
00:12:41.490 --> 00:12:43.470
you wash off the top of the skin

229
00:12:43.470 --> 00:12:45.540
and you'll be able to see the burrow.

230
00:12:45.540 --> 00:12:48.000
Then you take your little blade and scrape it

231
00:12:48.000 --> 00:12:50.670
and look in the microscope for the mites,

232
00:12:50.670 --> 00:12:52.080
the eggs and the feces.

233
00:12:52.080 --> 00:12:54.450
And if you're lucky and the patient is not,

234
00:12:54.450 --> 00:12:57.330
you may see the mite that are on your left and the eggs

235
00:12:57.330 --> 00:12:59.103
and fecal material on the right.

236
00:13:00.480 --> 00:13:03.150
Norwegian or crusted scabies

237
00:13:03.150 --> 00:13:06.930
is an overwhelming infection usually in HIV patients.

238
00:13:06.930 --> 00:13:09.063
Not all that itchy, however.

239
00:13:10.470 --> 00:13:12.120
How do you treat scabies?

240
00:13:12.120 --> 00:13:16.350
You launder bedding, clothing worn within 72 hours

241
00:13:16.350 --> 00:13:18.720
or you stick it in a bag and suffocate 'em.

242
00:13:18.720 --> 00:13:21.000
Treat the patient, their contacts,

243
00:13:21.000 --> 00:13:25.680
anybody living in the same household with permethrin 5%.

244
00:13:25.680 --> 00:13:27.390
And you treat from the neck down,

245
00:13:27.390 --> 00:13:30.030
the stuff usually doesn't get into the scalp

246
00:13:30.030 --> 00:13:31.950
and you may or may not repeat it in a week

247
00:13:31.950 --> 00:13:34.080
depending on what you want to do.

248
00:13:34.080 --> 00:13:37.320
Ivermectin is effective for Norwegian scabies.

249
00:13:37.320 --> 00:13:40.413
If you can find a leftover from the COVID epidemic.

250
00:13:41.550 --> 00:13:44.760
Benzoyl peroxide lotion, a few other things,

251
00:13:44.760 --> 00:13:46.533
Eurax available over the counter.

252
00:13:48.240 --> 00:13:51.960
This is Rhus dermatitis, also known

253
00:13:51.960 --> 00:13:56.960
as toxicodendron dermatitis, also known as poison ivy.

254
00:13:57.210 --> 00:14:00.570
And this happens when you contact the sap from the plants

255
00:14:00.570 --> 00:14:03.630
in this particular plant family.

256
00:14:03.630 --> 00:14:08.130
Poison ivy, poison oak, poison sumac, mangoes.

257
00:14:08.130 --> 00:14:09.840
If you live in Hawaii,

258
00:14:09.840 --> 00:14:12.930
a lot of the dermatitis is in peeling mangoes

259
00:14:12.930 --> 00:14:14.580
as you see in that area.

260
00:14:14.580 --> 00:14:17.910
And of course, the ubiquitous Japanese lacquer tree

261
00:14:17.910 --> 00:14:20.310
that we all have in our backyards.

262
00:14:20.310 --> 00:14:21.600
And you see poison ivy.

263
00:14:21.600 --> 00:14:24.870
So linear lesions, you may see vesicles,

264
00:14:24.870 --> 00:14:28.650
redness may take up to eight hours after exposure

265
00:14:28.650 --> 00:14:32.040
or even a week before you see these things come on.

266
00:14:32.040 --> 00:14:33.780
How are you gonna treat it?

267
00:14:33.780 --> 00:14:36.030
If you're gonna decontaminate it,

268
00:14:36.030 --> 00:14:39.090
you know, with soap and water, you gotta be quick.

269
00:14:39.090 --> 00:14:42.060
Once it's occurred, you can treat it with compresses.

270
00:14:42.060 --> 00:14:44.880
Oral antihistamines don't work all that well.

271
00:14:44.880 --> 00:14:48.390
Steroids do, but they typically have to be high potency.

272
00:14:48.390 --> 00:14:51.840
And more recently, the recommendation is systemic steroids

273
00:14:51.840 --> 00:14:54.750
as long as 2 to 3 weeks of prednisone,

274
00:14:54.750 --> 00:14:57.810
so that you don't rebound over that period of time.

275
00:14:57.810 --> 00:15:00.030
You can inject triamcinolone,

276
00:15:00.030 --> 00:15:02.640
you may have to do more than once as well

277
00:15:02.640 --> 00:15:03.753
to keep that treated.

278
00:15:04.860 --> 00:15:07.200
Moving to contact dermatitis,

279
00:15:07.200 --> 00:15:12.090
you can almost kind of envision where the nickel band is

280
00:15:12.090 --> 00:15:13.683
around this person's wrist.

281
00:15:16.590 --> 00:15:17.703
Case number four.

282
00:15:20.850 --> 00:15:22.053
Look at that carefully.

283
00:15:22.950 --> 00:15:25.173
Look at the hair follicles carefully.

284
00:15:27.750 --> 00:15:30.540
This is a 55-year-old male congressman,

285
00:15:30.540 --> 00:15:33.330
complained of a new rash on his chest

286
00:15:33.330 --> 00:15:36.960
after returning from a business trip with a female lobbyist.

287
00:15:36.960 --> 00:15:39.090
He admitted to spending an inordinate amount

288
00:15:39.090 --> 00:15:41.280
of time having meaningful conversations

289
00:15:41.280 --> 00:15:43.680
with her in a hot tub.

290
00:15:43.680 --> 00:15:47.100
Of course, while masked and socially distancing.

291
00:15:47.100 --> 00:15:48.990
Which one of the following would you recommend

292
00:15:48.990 --> 00:15:51.510
for the management of this condition?

293
00:15:51.510 --> 00:15:53.280
Oral cephalexin,

294
00:15:53.280 --> 00:15:57.090
no pharmacologic therapy, but stay out of hot tubs,

295
00:15:57.090 --> 00:16:00.903
oral Bactrim or topical clotrimazole?

296
00:16:02.670 --> 00:16:03.903
See how you do.

297
00:16:06.270 --> 00:16:09.390
And you have voted for B, which is correct.

298
00:16:09.390 --> 00:16:11.193
Why? What's wrong with this patient?

299
00:16:12.990 --> 00:16:16.020
Has hot tub folliculitis, right?

300
00:16:16.020 --> 00:16:17.610
Those of you who thought about Bactrim

301
00:16:17.610 --> 00:16:19.950
weren't all that far off, okay?

302
00:16:19.950 --> 00:16:22.860
If you thought it was a staphylococcal folliculitis,

303
00:16:22.860 --> 00:16:23.693
which is not.

304
00:16:25.080 --> 00:16:26.610
So what is folliculitis?

305
00:16:26.610 --> 00:16:31.200
A superficial bacterial infection of the hair follicle.

306
00:16:31.200 --> 00:16:33.240
When you get a lot of these things together,

307
00:16:33.240 --> 00:16:35.130
you may get a furuncle.

308
00:16:35.130 --> 00:16:38.040
Those furuncle go to town and kind of coagulate,

309
00:16:38.040 --> 00:16:41.670
you get carbuncles and then you get purulent drainage

310
00:16:41.670 --> 00:16:43.710
from multiple follicles.

311
00:16:43.710 --> 00:16:47.250
And here's one furuncle waiting for Dr. Bard Parker

312
00:16:47.250 --> 00:16:49.083
to come and liberate his pus.

313
00:16:50.070 --> 00:16:55.070
Sycosis Barbae, folliculitis in the the beard area.

314
00:16:55.860 --> 00:16:58.170
Most folliculitis is staph aureus

315
00:16:58.170 --> 00:17:00.750
and your Bactrim folks that would help with it.

316
00:17:00.750 --> 00:17:02.220
But in the hot tub,

317
00:17:02.220 --> 00:17:04.710
and some of the hot springs like in Nevada

318
00:17:04.710 --> 00:17:07.683
and California, it's pseudomonas and aeromonas.

319
00:17:08.580 --> 00:17:11.220
Canada species, sometimes remotely,

320
00:17:11.220 --> 00:17:13.353
even non-TB microbacteria.

321
00:17:14.220 --> 00:17:15.810
The good thing about folliculitis,

322
00:17:15.810 --> 00:17:18.330
usually gets better on its own,

323
00:17:18.330 --> 00:17:19.920
but when there's extensive involvement

324
00:17:19.920 --> 00:17:23.130
or long lasting will treat it with antibiotics.

325
00:17:23.130 --> 00:17:25.290
Warm compresses help

326
00:17:25.290 --> 00:17:29.790
if there are furuncles or carbuncles

327
00:17:29.790 --> 00:17:31.440
and the valve invo...

328
00:17:31.440 --> 00:17:33.990
Excuse me, avoid shaving in areas

329
00:17:33.990 --> 00:17:36.390
where the folliculitis is present.

330
00:17:36.390 --> 00:17:38.460
With hot tub folliculitis,

331
00:17:38.460 --> 00:17:40.770
stay away from the contaminated water

332
00:17:40.770 --> 00:17:42.303
that usually does the trick.

333
00:17:43.410 --> 00:17:45.810
In severe cases, ciprofloxacin,

334
00:17:45.810 --> 00:17:47.820
which covers your gram negatives,

335
00:17:47.820 --> 00:17:49.863
would be a reasonable antibiotic to use.

336
00:17:50.940 --> 00:17:53.012
Mild staph folliculitis.

337
00:17:53.012 --> 00:17:56.120
If you're gonna treat it, you can use mupirocin

338
00:17:56.120 --> 00:18:00.150
or topical clindamycin if it's more severe

339
00:18:00.150 --> 00:18:02.130
and using oral therapy.

340
00:18:02.130 --> 00:18:05.498
If it's not MRSA, dicloxacillin or cephalexin,

341
00:18:05.498 --> 00:18:08.613
if it's MRSA, Bactrim, clindamycin, or doxy.

342
00:18:10.950 --> 00:18:14.490
Pseudofolliculitis barbae is not a folliculitis,

343
00:18:14.490 --> 00:18:16.050
it's an ingrown hair.

344
00:18:16.050 --> 00:18:18.990
Hair is cut too short and sharp, grow backwards

345
00:18:18.990 --> 00:18:21.450
and form inflammatory papules.

346
00:18:21.450 --> 00:18:23.550
The treatment of that is very simple.

347
00:18:23.550 --> 00:18:26.271
You do what I do, and you don't shave.

348
00:18:26.271 --> 00:18:27.450
(attendees laughing)

349
00:18:27.450 --> 00:18:31.530
Impetigo seen mostly in children.

350
00:18:31.530 --> 00:18:35.070
A contagious, superficial bacterial infection.

351
00:18:35.070 --> 00:18:38.460
Primary impetigo occurs on normal skin.

352
00:18:38.460 --> 00:18:42.843
Secondary in patients with things like abrasions or eczema.

353
00:18:44.370 --> 00:18:46.950
There are a couple different types of impetigo.

354
00:18:46.950 --> 00:18:50.490
Nonbullous impetigo is the most common form.

355
00:18:50.490 --> 00:18:55.490
Begins a papule, progressed to a thick golden crust.

356
00:18:55.590 --> 00:18:58.440
In the past, this was beta-strep,

357
00:18:58.440 --> 00:19:01.323
nowadays, 90% of it is staph aureus.

358
00:19:02.850 --> 00:19:04.650
Bullous impetigo.

359
00:19:04.650 --> 00:19:07.410
These are vesicles that become flaccid,

360
00:19:07.410 --> 00:19:10.050
yellow initially then turbid.

361
00:19:10.050 --> 00:19:12.573
This is staph aureus exclusively.

362
00:19:13.800 --> 00:19:17.970
Strep impetigo, again, rarely see in these days

363
00:19:17.970 --> 00:19:21.630
can go along with poststreptococcal glomerulonephritis.

364
00:19:21.630 --> 00:19:24.430
The board could ask you that, but I don't think it will.

365
00:19:25.350 --> 00:19:27.540
How do you treat impetigo?

366
00:19:27.540 --> 00:19:29.280
Limited number of lesions.

367
00:19:29.280 --> 00:19:32.670
Use Bactroban amongst others.

368
00:19:32.670 --> 00:19:34.680
If there are more of them, oral treatment

369
00:19:34.680 --> 00:19:36.900
if you don't think it's MRSA, again,

370
00:19:36.900 --> 00:19:39.030
cephalex you think it is.

371
00:19:39.030 --> 00:19:41.733
Clindamycin, Bactrim or even linezolid.

372
00:19:43.590 --> 00:19:46.383
This is a patient who has erysipelas.

373
00:19:47.370 --> 00:19:51.150
This is a cellulitis, a beta-strep cellulitis.

374
00:19:51.150 --> 00:19:54.150
These folks tend to be pretty darn sick.

375
00:19:54.150 --> 00:19:57.270
Often they're septic, high fever, mental status changes

376
00:19:57.270 --> 00:19:58.860
if they're elderly.

377
00:19:58.860 --> 00:20:02.700
The lesion has a well demarcated erythematous border

378
00:20:02.700 --> 00:20:05.733
and these folks often need admission for IV antibiotics.

379
00:20:06.630 --> 00:20:08.850
If they're not all that sick,

380
00:20:08.850 --> 00:20:11.430
then you can use oral medication

381
00:20:11.430 --> 00:20:13.593
that will work for strep infections.

382
00:20:16.470 --> 00:20:18.450
All right, case number five.

383
00:20:18.450 --> 00:20:19.293
Moving along.

384
00:20:20.880 --> 00:20:23.310
You see this one okay?

385
00:20:23.310 --> 00:20:26.310
You've probably seen this one a lot in the past.

386
00:20:26.310 --> 00:20:29.460
16-year-old female would like to be treated

387
00:20:29.460 --> 00:20:32.190
for this facial rash, not responding

388
00:20:32.190 --> 00:20:35.220
to over the counter cleansing preparations.

389
00:20:35.220 --> 00:20:37.590
Her high school prom is three months away,

390
00:20:37.590 --> 00:20:39.180
she wants to look good.

391
00:20:39.180 --> 00:20:40.983
She's not sexually active.

392
00:20:43.368 --> 00:20:45.600
Which one the following would you recommend

393
00:20:45.600 --> 00:20:48.390
for the management of this condition?

394
00:20:48.390 --> 00:20:50.760
A topical retinoid alone.

395
00:20:50.760 --> 00:20:53.400
Topical clindamycin alone.

396
00:20:53.400 --> 00:20:56.310
A topical retinoid with benzoyl peroxide

397
00:20:56.310 --> 00:21:00.033
and oral doxycycline or isotretinoin?

398
00:21:05.579 --> 00:21:07.500
And we're gonna go with C, which is correct.

399
00:21:07.500 --> 00:21:09.900
And what's wrong with this patient?

400
00:21:09.900 --> 00:21:10.733
What she got?

401
00:21:12.510 --> 00:21:13.980
She got acne.

402
00:21:13.980 --> 00:21:15.993
Acne vulgaris, right?

403
00:21:17.340 --> 00:21:21.270
She has inflammatory acne vulgaris to be exact.

404
00:21:21.270 --> 00:21:24.933
Here we see a couple of pictures, patients with acne.

405
00:21:26.130 --> 00:21:29.370
Acne is an androgen-mediated disease.

406
00:21:29.370 --> 00:21:33.120
It happens when our hormones kick in, our androgens kick in.

407
00:21:33.120 --> 00:21:37.320
The androgens simulate sebum production from the follicles

408
00:21:37.320 --> 00:21:40.410
and keratinocytes proliferate.

409
00:21:40.410 --> 00:21:44.853
They make keratin, which plugs up the duct of the follicle,

410
00:21:46.290 --> 00:21:48.700
bacteria that stays in the area, cutibacterium

411
00:21:49.740 --> 00:21:51.870
is the current name for it.

412
00:21:51.870 --> 00:21:54.870
It proliferates in that plugged follicle

413
00:21:54.870 --> 00:21:56.700
and produces inflammation

414
00:21:56.700 --> 00:21:59.523
through inflammatory substances it secretes.

415
00:22:00.360 --> 00:22:03.183
That's what causes what we see in acne.

416
00:22:04.110 --> 00:22:07.800
The board may ask you about different kinds of acne lesions,

417
00:22:07.800 --> 00:22:12.630
closed comedones or whitehead, open comedones or blackheads

418
00:22:12.630 --> 00:22:15.060
that's due to the plugging of the follicle

419
00:22:15.060 --> 00:22:16.413
with the keratinocytes.

420
00:22:17.310 --> 00:22:21.180
With inflammation, you get nodules or papules, or pustules

421
00:22:21.180 --> 00:22:23.430
and eventually different kinds of scars

422
00:22:23.430 --> 00:22:24.843
that are difficult to treat.

423
00:22:25.980 --> 00:22:28.920
Here we have a patient with acne,

424
00:22:28.920 --> 00:22:30.960
inflammatory acne on the forehead,

425
00:22:30.960 --> 00:22:35.040
another one that we saw earlier around the mouth.

426
00:22:35.040 --> 00:22:37.770
This patient has an inflammatory cyst

427
00:22:37.770 --> 00:22:40.770
and the dreaded black rectangular eye syndrome

428
00:22:40.770 --> 00:22:43.383
that we often see in dermatology textbooks.

429
00:22:45.270 --> 00:22:47.160
Most common areas of acne

430
00:22:47.160 --> 00:22:50.520
are where there is sebaceous gland activity.

431
00:22:50.520 --> 00:22:52.410
That's why you see in the face,

432
00:22:52.410 --> 00:22:55.833
the upper chest, upper back, and the upper arms.

433
00:22:57.030 --> 00:22:58.560
So how do you treat acne?

434
00:22:58.560 --> 00:23:01.110
We're gonna talk a little bit about this in more detail

435
00:23:01.110 --> 00:23:05.130
because acne is the most common skin condition seen by us

436
00:23:05.130 --> 00:23:09.330
and by dermatologists is we treat comedonal acne

437
00:23:09.330 --> 00:23:11.013
with a keratinolytic agent.

438
00:23:11.880 --> 00:23:14.460
If there's mild inflammation with it,

439
00:23:14.460 --> 00:23:18.220
we continue that and add benzoyl peroxide

440
00:23:19.080 --> 00:23:21.660
or a different topical antibiotic.

441
00:23:21.660 --> 00:23:25.050
With moderate inflammatory acne like our patient,

442
00:23:25.050 --> 00:23:27.480
we're going to add to the keratinolytic agent

443
00:23:27.480 --> 00:23:31.800
and benzoyl peroxide a systemic antibiotic.

444
00:23:31.800 --> 00:23:34.353
And those who have bad nodulocystic,

445
00:23:35.430 --> 00:23:38.910
we can use the big gun isotretinoin

446
00:23:38.910 --> 00:23:40.743
or used to be called Accutane.

447
00:23:42.750 --> 00:23:45.270
What are topical keratinolytics we have?

448
00:23:45.270 --> 00:23:50.270
Tretinoin or Retin-A, adapalene, work about the same.

449
00:23:50.370 --> 00:23:53.400
Adapalene is better tolerated and now available

450
00:23:53.400 --> 00:23:56.970
in combination with benzoyl peroxide or with Retin-A,

451
00:23:56.970 --> 00:24:00.630
you have to do it at different time as benzoyl peroxide

452
00:24:00.630 --> 00:24:02.193
because of deactivation.

453
00:24:03.060 --> 00:24:05.040
Again, retinoids tend to be irritating,

454
00:24:05.040 --> 00:24:07.090
especially if you start 'em at high dose.

455
00:24:07.980 --> 00:24:11.460
Tazarotene been around for a while, is teratogenic

456
00:24:11.460 --> 00:24:14.640
as all retinoids have that capability.

457
00:24:14.640 --> 00:24:18.470
A new one on the market, trifarotene 4th generation,

458
00:24:18.470 --> 00:24:22.293
less skin irritation and more expensive.

459
00:24:24.000 --> 00:24:28.800
Azelaic acid is keratotic and anti-inflammatory.

460
00:24:28.800 --> 00:24:30.780
Also depigmenting.

461
00:24:30.780 --> 00:24:33.303
You can use it to treat hyperpigmentation.

462
00:24:35.760 --> 00:24:38.201
Moving on to topical antibacterials,

463
00:24:38.201 --> 00:24:40.830
benzoyl peroxide has been around for a while.

464
00:24:40.830 --> 00:24:45.060
The good thing about it is there's no resistance yet

465
00:24:45.060 --> 00:24:48.540
of the acne bacteria to BP.

466
00:24:48.540 --> 00:24:51.810
Usually given twice a day, it's a peroxide

467
00:24:51.810 --> 00:24:54.303
so it can bleach things, so be careful with that.

468
00:24:55.260 --> 00:24:59.370
We sometimes combine it with other topical antibiotics

469
00:24:59.370 --> 00:25:01.230
so we can use the other antibiotic

470
00:25:01.230 --> 00:25:03.033
without worrying about resistance.

471
00:25:05.782 --> 00:25:08.730
No longer recommended that you use things

472
00:25:08.730 --> 00:25:10.862
like erythromycin and clindamycin

473
00:25:10.862 --> 00:25:14.040
and tetracycline topically by themselves

474
00:25:14.040 --> 00:25:18.180
only because resistance is high, use it with BP.

475
00:25:18.180 --> 00:25:22.830
Metronidazole gel can be used for acne as well.

476
00:25:22.830 --> 00:25:26.550
Dapsone available more for women

477
00:25:26.550 --> 00:25:31.550
with acne lesions and it doesn't cause glucose-6PD issues

478
00:25:31.680 --> 00:25:33.033
when you use it topically.

479
00:25:34.590 --> 00:25:36.630
Systemic antibiotics.

480
00:25:36.630 --> 00:25:39.510
Try not to use them more than three months.

481
00:25:39.510 --> 00:25:43.440
Tetracycline has been, the one you used over time,

482
00:25:43.440 --> 00:25:44.943
of course, not in children.

483
00:25:45.870 --> 00:25:48.421
It's not as effective though as minocycline

484
00:25:48.421 --> 00:25:49.593
and doxycycline.

485
00:25:50.700 --> 00:25:52.440
Minocycline is effective,

486
00:25:52.440 --> 00:25:54.390
has allowed systemic side effects

487
00:25:54.390 --> 00:25:58.170
including lupus-like reactions and for that reason,

488
00:25:58.170 --> 00:26:00.120
not used all that often.

489
00:26:00.120 --> 00:26:03.730
Doxycycline easy to use around food

490
00:26:04.650 --> 00:26:07.833
is photosensitizing, so be aware of that.

491
00:26:08.670 --> 00:26:11.220
There's a new one on the market, sarecycline,

492
00:26:11.220 --> 00:26:14.853
again, more narrow spectrum, also more expensive.

493
00:26:15.930 --> 00:26:19.293
Now, how many of you are aware of the use of a Wood's lamp?

494
00:26:20.280 --> 00:26:22.890
And Wood's lamp's a good thing to have in your armamentarium

495
00:26:22.890 --> 00:26:25.740
for many diseases, you know, recommend you carry

496
00:26:25.740 --> 00:26:29.340
that in your pockets at all times.

497
00:26:29.340 --> 00:26:33.000
I know Dr. Weismiller usually recommends

498
00:26:33.000 --> 00:26:36.750
with get togethers like this that over the course of time,

499
00:26:36.750 --> 00:26:39.510
you make friends with those people sitting around with you

500
00:26:39.510 --> 00:26:41.880
maybe go out and have dinner or something.

501
00:26:41.880 --> 00:26:45.480
If you do that and you find a liking for that person

502
00:26:45.480 --> 00:26:48.690
before you take that relationship to a higher level,

503
00:26:48.690 --> 00:26:52.980
take out your Wood's lamp, have them pee in a cup for you

504
00:26:52.980 --> 00:26:54.990
and scan the cup.

505
00:26:54.990 --> 00:26:57.870
And if the contents fluoresce,

506
00:26:57.870 --> 00:27:00.510
they're probably taking doxycycline for chlamydia

507
00:27:00.510 --> 00:27:02.040
and you don't want anything to do with them

508
00:27:02.040 --> 00:27:05.820
for the rest of the course.
(attendees laughing)

509
00:27:05.820 --> 00:27:10.080
Other antibiotics he used for acne include erythromycin.

510
00:27:10.080 --> 00:27:12.240
Again, azithromycin, Bactrim.

511
00:27:12.240 --> 00:27:15.603
Be careful about resistance to those antibiotics.

512
00:27:16.620 --> 00:27:18.810
Again, three months systemic antibiotics,

513
00:27:18.810 --> 00:27:21.450
you can switch abruptly from oral to topical

514
00:27:21.450 --> 00:27:22.563
without tapering.

515
00:27:23.490 --> 00:27:27.240
Again, don't use topical and oral antibiotics together

516
00:27:27.240 --> 00:27:29.463
unless one of those is benzoyl peroxide.

517
00:27:30.960 --> 00:27:32.940
Oral contraceptives.

518
00:27:32.940 --> 00:27:34.560
There are a number of them FDA approved

519
00:27:34.560 --> 00:27:35.730
for treatment of acne.

520
00:27:35.730 --> 00:27:39.510
It's the progestin component that's important here.

521
00:27:39.510 --> 00:27:42.360
You want to use one that's non-androgenic.

522
00:27:42.360 --> 00:27:44.340
And these four have been recommended

523
00:27:44.340 --> 00:27:45.723
and approved by FDA.

524
00:27:47.550 --> 00:27:51.630
Spironalactone and anti-androgen, again, use it in women.

525
00:27:51.630 --> 00:27:54.030
It grows the breasts in men.

526
00:27:54.030 --> 00:27:56.403
It's not FDA approved, however, for acne.

527
00:27:57.480 --> 00:28:01.140
There's a new cream that came out, clascoterone,

528
00:28:01.140 --> 00:28:03.750
which is a topical antigen receptor inhibitor.

529
00:28:03.750 --> 00:28:06.990
So kind of like a topical spironolactone of sorts,

530
00:28:06.990 --> 00:28:09.243
which you can use both in men and women.

531
00:28:11.395 --> 00:28:13.620
What about isotretinoin?

532
00:28:13.620 --> 00:28:18.007
This is a medicine that can cure acne given over

533
00:28:18.007 --> 00:28:19.650
a 12 to 20-week course.

534
00:28:19.650 --> 00:28:22.620
Lots of side effects, the worst being that

535
00:28:22.620 --> 00:28:24.690
is highly teratogenic.

536
00:28:24.690 --> 00:28:27.000
So if you're gonna use this with a patient,

537
00:28:27.000 --> 00:28:29.430
both you and the patient have to register

538
00:28:29.430 --> 00:28:31.383
with the iPLEDGE program.

539
00:28:32.520 --> 00:28:34.800
And that is a pledge that you and the patient

540
00:28:34.800 --> 00:28:37.080
and that you don't let them get pregnant

541
00:28:37.080 --> 00:28:41.310
that need to be on contraception and/or avoiding sex

542
00:28:41.310 --> 00:28:42.963
and not get pregnant on them.

543
00:28:44.520 --> 00:28:46.560
There are life-based treatments for acne.

544
00:28:46.560 --> 00:28:48.330
Again, something the dermatologist

545
00:28:48.330 --> 00:28:50.850
will typically tend to use.

546
00:28:50.850 --> 00:28:53.190
Not all that greatly effective.

547
00:28:53.190 --> 00:28:54.690
If you enjoy being a surgeon,

548
00:28:54.690 --> 00:28:59.690
you can use your Comedo extractor and suck out those zits,

549
00:29:00.210 --> 00:29:01.320
a lot of fun.

550
00:29:01.320 --> 00:29:03.450
If you have abscesses, you can drain them

551
00:29:03.450 --> 00:29:07.110
or you can inject them if they're cystic with triamcinolone

552
00:29:07.110 --> 00:29:08.823
and make them shrink down quicker.

553
00:29:10.140 --> 00:29:14.847
Topical tea tree oil is an alternative treatment for acne.

554
00:29:16.860 --> 00:29:18.450
There is some data that it works,

555
00:29:18.450 --> 00:29:20.553
but it's effective and it's kind of slow.

556
00:29:21.450 --> 00:29:24.360
Who should you send to the dermatologist?

557
00:29:24.360 --> 00:29:26.010
Refractory lesions despite

558
00:29:26.010 --> 00:29:28.200
the appropriate therapy you're giving.

559
00:29:28.200 --> 00:29:30.600
You think they're bad enough to need isotretinoin,

560
00:29:30.600 --> 00:29:32.670
you might wanna let them start it

561
00:29:32.670 --> 00:29:34.560
and then continue if you need to.

562
00:29:34.560 --> 00:29:36.906
Acne scars are hard to get rid of.

563
00:29:36.906 --> 00:29:38.940
As soon as you're really good at dermabrasions

564
00:29:38.940 --> 00:29:41.290
and things like that and let them work on that.

565
00:29:42.450 --> 00:29:45.240
Leaving acne vulgaris, we have another acne.

566
00:29:45.240 --> 00:29:46.953
This is acne Rosacea.

567
00:29:48.600 --> 00:29:53.310
Here we see more rosacea, forehead, cheeks are involved.

568
00:29:53.310 --> 00:29:55.803
Here, we have more involvement of the nose.

569
00:29:56.850 --> 00:30:01.770
Rosacea is seen more often in women over 30

570
00:30:01.770 --> 00:30:03.930
of Celtic ethnicity.

571
00:30:03.930 --> 00:30:05.220
We don't know what causes it.

572
00:30:05.220 --> 00:30:09.513
There is some enthusiasm for it being due to Demodex mites.

573
00:30:11.400 --> 00:30:14.430
It's chronic, intermittent, involves forehead, cheeks,

574
00:30:14.430 --> 00:30:16.980
nose, around the eyes.

575
00:30:16.980 --> 00:30:19.170
The board may very well ask you

576
00:30:19.170 --> 00:30:21.843
the primary features of rosacea.

577
00:30:22.800 --> 00:30:26.013
Erythema, you can see a flushing with that.

578
00:30:27.210 --> 00:30:31.860
Papules and pustules and telangiectasias.

579
00:30:31.860 --> 00:30:34.740
Those are the three primary features.

580
00:30:34.740 --> 00:30:36.030
You can also get something called

581
00:30:36.030 --> 00:30:39.690
a rhinophyma bulbus red nose.

582
00:30:39.690 --> 00:30:43.020
Our friend WC Fields over there, had that.

583
00:30:43.020 --> 00:30:44.610
He was a big drinker and thought,

584
00:30:44.610 --> 00:30:47.820
well, maybe the drinking caused that, but it doesn't.

585
00:30:47.820 --> 00:30:50.580
But drinking does causes the rash

586
00:30:50.580 --> 00:30:54.510
to flush and become more apparent because of vasal dilates.

587
00:30:54.510 --> 00:30:59.400
So spicy foods, alcohol, niacin,

588
00:30:59.400 --> 00:31:00.960
anything that vasodilate you

589
00:31:00.960 --> 00:31:03.120
will make the rosacea rash come up.

590
00:31:03.120 --> 00:31:04.830
So if you want to diagnose it,

591
00:31:04.830 --> 00:31:05.790
if you're not sure you have it,

592
00:31:05.790 --> 00:31:08.250
give your patients some niacin, watch them flush,

593
00:31:08.250 --> 00:31:10.503
say, oh, you have rosacea, right?

594
00:31:11.400 --> 00:31:14.190
How do you treat it? Topical antibiotics

595
00:31:14.190 --> 00:31:16.650
for the papules and pustules.

596
00:31:16.650 --> 00:31:18.240
Metrogel, you can use that.

597
00:31:18.240 --> 00:31:21.210
Don't use the vaginal preparation,

598
00:31:21.210 --> 00:31:23.403
use the skin preparation.

599
00:31:24.570 --> 00:31:28.440
Azelaic acid, benzoyl peroxide, clindamycin.

600
00:31:28.440 --> 00:31:30.270
For the erythema and flushing,

601
00:31:30.270 --> 00:31:34.653
you can use brimonidine or you can use oxymethazone.

602
00:31:35.730 --> 00:31:40.113
Carvedilol can also help prevent flushing in patients.

603
00:31:41.430 --> 00:31:44.190
For again, the nodular areas if they're worse

604
00:31:44.190 --> 00:31:46.470
and topical therapy doesn't work,

605
00:31:46.470 --> 00:31:50.820
the same antibiotics we typically use for acne vulgaris.

606
00:31:50.820 --> 00:31:54.120
And retinoids can also be used in severe cases,

607
00:31:54.120 --> 00:31:57.513
actually, retinoid can also work for rosacea.

608
00:31:58.680 --> 00:32:02.550
Now this is a patient who has seborrheic dermatitis

609
00:32:02.550 --> 00:32:06.074
and acute Seroquel deficiency, I think.

610
00:32:06.074 --> 00:32:08.580
(attendees laughing)

611
00:32:08.580 --> 00:32:11.280
A little bit of seborrheic dermatitis again here,

612
00:32:11.280 --> 00:32:14.700
kind of a greasy-looking rash in the face

613
00:32:14.700 --> 00:32:16.960
or in the sternum area.

614
00:32:16.960 --> 00:32:20.730
We tend to see seborrheic dermatitis in young infants.

615
00:32:20.730 --> 00:32:22.110
We can also see in adults,

616
00:32:22.110 --> 00:32:24.840
you see in adults coming outta nowhere.

617
00:32:24.840 --> 00:32:26.880
Think about HIV.

618
00:32:26.880 --> 00:32:29.400
Think about Parkinson's disease.

619
00:32:29.400 --> 00:32:30.570
In Parkinson's disease,

620
00:32:30.570 --> 00:32:34.233
L-dopa may actually improve the dermatitis as well.

621
00:32:35.280 --> 00:32:39.753
For typical young kids with seborrheic dermatitis,

622
00:32:40.710 --> 00:32:45.153
you can use topical antifungals or low-potency steroids.

623
00:32:46.770 --> 00:32:50.580
On the scalp, antifungal shampoos like selenium sulfide

624
00:32:50.580 --> 00:32:53.253
or ketoconazole work well.

625
00:32:55.050 --> 00:32:57.120
Perioral dermatitis.

626
00:32:57.120 --> 00:33:00.690
This is kind of an acne lookalike, a mimic.

627
00:33:00.690 --> 00:33:03.660
Typical story here is she says, "Well, doc,

628
00:33:03.660 --> 00:33:07.350
I got this rash, I put some of the steroid stuff on it

629
00:33:07.350 --> 00:33:09.150
and this is what I got."

630
00:33:09.150 --> 00:33:10.083
And it's typical.

631
00:33:11.790 --> 00:33:14.820
With mild involvement, we use topical metronidazole

632
00:33:14.820 --> 00:33:17.700
like we do for rosacea, topical erythromycin

633
00:33:17.700 --> 00:33:20.154
or pimecrolimus.

634
00:33:20.154 --> 00:33:24.753
More than mild, same oral antibiotics we use for acne.

635
00:33:26.100 --> 00:33:31.100
Lupus erythematosus, nasty rash, nasty disease.

636
00:33:31.650 --> 00:33:33.753
As they say, the mask of the wolf.

637
00:33:35.190 --> 00:33:39.633
Lupus can be chronic cutaneous lupus, subacute or acute.

638
00:33:40.770 --> 00:33:43.680
Most patients with lupus will have mucocutaneous lesions

639
00:33:43.680 --> 00:33:46.080
at some time during their illness.

640
00:33:46.080 --> 00:33:49.950
The butterfly malar rash being the most common,

641
00:33:49.950 --> 00:33:54.450
it tends to spare the nasolabial folds, for some reason.

642
00:33:54.450 --> 00:33:58.353
Sun exposure makes this worse, it's photosensitive.

643
00:33:59.280 --> 00:34:02.430
You see another young lady who has a lupus rash.

644
00:34:02.430 --> 00:34:03.873
This is discoid lupus.

645
00:34:05.010 --> 00:34:06.900
So how do you treat lupus?

646
00:34:06.900 --> 00:34:08.640
Keep 'em out of the sun.

647
00:34:08.640 --> 00:34:12.270
Stay away from cigarettes and aggravating drugs.

648
00:34:12.270 --> 00:34:14.670
Topical steroids usually more potent

649
00:34:14.670 --> 00:34:17.130
than we usually use on the face.

650
00:34:17.130 --> 00:34:20.430
You can use topical calcineurin inhibitors,

651
00:34:20.430 --> 00:34:24.060
systemic anti-malarials like Plaquenil,

652
00:34:24.060 --> 00:34:27.903
and even methotrexate if it's not responding.

653
00:34:29.370 --> 00:34:30.843
Case number six.

654
00:34:31.950 --> 00:34:33.693
The case of the spotted man.

655
00:34:35.250 --> 00:34:40.113
21-year-old male pale spots on his back and his upper chest.

656
00:34:42.390 --> 00:34:44.310
Despite treatment with a topical agent,

657
00:34:44.310 --> 00:34:46.770
they're now essentially unchanged.

658
00:34:46.770 --> 00:34:50.100
These areas should now be treated which of the following,

659
00:34:50.100 --> 00:34:54.180
Benzathine penicillin G, if you can find it.

660
00:34:54.180 --> 00:34:58.353
Pimecrolimus, oral fluconazole or prednisone?

661
00:35:03.750 --> 00:35:07.710
And we're gonna use Diflucan, good for you, good for you.

662
00:35:07.710 --> 00:35:09.393
Why? What's wrong with this guy?

663
00:35:11.580 --> 00:35:13.683
He has tinea versicolor, right?

664
00:35:14.709 --> 00:35:15.542
Okay.

665
00:35:17.370 --> 00:35:20.130
These are hypopigmented lesions.

666
00:35:20.130 --> 00:35:24.210
Pityriasis alba is all above vitiligo, tinea versicolor,

667
00:35:24.210 --> 00:35:25.960
post-inflammatory hypopigmentation.

668
00:35:27.570 --> 00:35:31.050
These are all hypopigmented things.

669
00:35:31.050 --> 00:35:34.440
Here we have a child with pityriasis alba.

670
00:35:34.440 --> 00:35:36.150
You can see the hypopigmentation,

671
00:35:36.150 --> 00:35:38.400
the forehead around the cheeks.

672
00:35:38.400 --> 00:35:40.030
Don't know exactly what causes it,

673
00:35:40.030 --> 00:35:42.330
don't know exactly how to treat it.

674
00:35:42.330 --> 00:35:44.610
Often we do a topical steroids,

675
00:35:44.610 --> 00:35:46.293
tends to get better over time.

676
00:35:47.130 --> 00:35:51.150
Here's a patient with vitiligo, fairly extensive.

677
00:35:51.150 --> 00:35:52.920
This tends to come in combination

678
00:35:52.920 --> 00:35:54.870
with other autoimmune diseases.

679
00:35:54.870 --> 00:35:58.293
So think about it with B12 deficiencies in thyroiditis.

680
00:36:00.120 --> 00:36:02.280
Tinea versicolor, which our patient has,

681
00:36:02.280 --> 00:36:07.280
fungus of multiple colors caused by Malassezia species

682
00:36:07.710 --> 00:36:10.860
when it converts from a budding to a mycelial form.

683
00:36:10.860 --> 00:36:15.000
That happens with heat, humidity, steroids, et cetera,

684
00:36:15.000 --> 00:36:17.460
and where there's high sebaceous activity.

685
00:36:17.460 --> 00:36:18.960
So who gets this?

686
00:36:18.960 --> 00:36:22.230
Younger people typically in the summer.

687
00:36:22.230 --> 00:36:24.540
In the summertime, they're tanning elsewhere

688
00:36:24.540 --> 00:36:26.370
and not over those lesions,

689
00:36:26.370 --> 00:36:29.520
and they make 'em even more obvious for you to see.

690
00:36:29.520 --> 00:36:32.190
They start as circular maculas and enlarges.

691
00:36:32.190 --> 00:36:36.196
They start off as tan or brown lesions, eventually,

692
00:36:36.196 --> 00:36:39.330
hypopigmented as they get older.

693
00:36:39.330 --> 00:36:41.880
A pottery scale means they're active.

694
00:36:41.880 --> 00:36:44.100
Get your Wood's lamp out, shine it.

695
00:36:44.100 --> 00:36:47.253
It's usually a yellow fluorescent over the area.

696
00:36:48.360 --> 00:36:49.770
How do you treat 'em?

697
00:36:49.770 --> 00:36:51.720
Limited amounts of disease.

698
00:36:51.720 --> 00:36:55.200
Topical antifungals, selenium sulfide,

699
00:36:55.200 --> 00:36:57.813
terbinafine, Selsun Blue.

700
00:36:59.430 --> 00:37:01.770
More extensive lesions, oral involvement

701
00:37:01.770 --> 00:37:04.170
like itraconazole or diflucan,

702
00:37:04.170 --> 00:37:08.040
stay away from oral ketoconazole because of the liver.

703
00:37:08.040 --> 00:37:10.320
If they have a lot of lesions,

704
00:37:10.320 --> 00:37:12.930
you can prophylax them against recurrence

705
00:37:12.930 --> 00:37:15.680
with ketoconazole or itraconazole.

706
00:37:15.680 --> 00:37:18.690
And tinea versicolor is in the Tinea family.

707
00:37:18.690 --> 00:37:21.063
Tinea means nothing more than fungus.

708
00:37:21.900 --> 00:37:23.880
We define them by sight.

709
00:37:23.880 --> 00:37:27.270
Tinea capitis in the head, tinea corporis in the body,

710
00:37:27.270 --> 00:37:29.520
tinea pedis in the feet.

711
00:37:29.520 --> 00:37:31.710
Tinea versicolor, multiple colors,

712
00:37:31.710 --> 00:37:35.820
tinea gladiatorum in high school and college wrestlers,

713
00:37:35.820 --> 00:37:38.852
tinea incognito in FBI agents,

714
00:37:38.852 --> 00:37:40.530
(attendees laughing)

715
00:37:40.530 --> 00:37:43.653
or folks who steal signs for football teams.

716
00:37:44.730 --> 00:37:46.920
Here's tinea corporis.

717
00:37:46.920 --> 00:37:49.620
Notice the well-defined margin.

718
00:37:49.620 --> 00:37:51.060
Here's tinea incognito.

719
00:37:51.060 --> 00:37:55.650
No, it's not FBI agents, this is tinea treated with steroids

720
00:37:55.650 --> 00:37:59.280
and now it's kind of hard to figure out what the heck it is.

721
00:37:59.280 --> 00:38:01.440
This is erythrasma.

722
00:38:01.440 --> 00:38:05.013
The board loves erythrasma, always has a question on it.

723
00:38:06.240 --> 00:38:09.900
And erythrasma shows up in the same places as tinea,

724
00:38:09.900 --> 00:38:12.120
typically under the breast and the groin area,

725
00:38:12.120 --> 00:38:15.930
and the axilla kind of acts the same way as well,

726
00:38:15.930 --> 00:38:19.590
but it's due to corynebacterium, not fungus.

727
00:38:19.590 --> 00:38:22.023
If you get out that Wood's lamp and shine it,

728
00:38:22.023 --> 00:38:27.000
it's a coral pink, coral red fluorescence, really pretty.

729
00:38:27.000 --> 00:38:29.130
And that makes the diagnosis.

730
00:38:29.130 --> 00:38:33.450
If you find that you treat 'em with topical macrolides

731
00:38:33.450 --> 00:38:36.363
or if it's worse, oral macrolides.

732
00:38:38.580 --> 00:38:40.290
Tinea capitis.

733
00:38:40.290 --> 00:38:44.370
Here, we see loss of hair from tinea capitis.

734
00:38:44.370 --> 00:38:45.720
If it gets severe enough

735
00:38:45.720 --> 00:38:47.790
and you get a real bad inflammatory response,

736
00:38:47.790 --> 00:38:50.400
we call it a Kerion, with a K,

737
00:38:50.400 --> 00:38:53.433
not with a C like vultures, like a K.

738
00:38:54.360 --> 00:38:57.540
The board may try to trick you on tinea capitis.

739
00:38:57.540 --> 00:38:58.470
The trick is,

740
00:38:58.470 --> 00:39:02.520
they want you to treat this topically and don't buy it.

741
00:39:02.520 --> 00:39:05.820
Tinea capitis is oral treatment, griseofulvin

742
00:39:05.820 --> 00:39:09.510
or terbinafine of different formulations

743
00:39:09.510 --> 00:39:11.970
and different lengths of treatment.

744
00:39:11.970 --> 00:39:15.270
Itraconazole, fluconazole will also work.

745
00:39:15.270 --> 00:39:18.420
With a Karion, you may wanna use steroids

746
00:39:18.420 --> 00:39:20.280
to decrease that inflammatory response

747
00:39:20.280 --> 00:39:23.310
while you're treating with an antifungal.

748
00:39:23.310 --> 00:39:27.960
And you can prophylac others in the household topically,

749
00:39:27.960 --> 00:39:30.573
but don't treat the patient topically.

750
00:39:32.040 --> 00:39:33.960
Traction alopecia.

751
00:39:33.960 --> 00:39:36.180
Here, that's braided too tightly

752
00:39:36.180 --> 00:39:39.090
and you have some hair loss as a result.

753
00:39:39.090 --> 00:39:43.590
Androgenic alopecia, a male pattern baldness,

754
00:39:43.590 --> 00:39:45.630
often sometimes seen in women.

755
00:39:45.630 --> 00:39:49.980
And this is patchy hair loss called alopecia areata.

756
00:39:49.980 --> 00:39:52.390
Also an autoimmune disease process

757
00:39:53.430 --> 00:39:56.490
associated with thyroiditis and vitiligo.

758
00:39:56.490 --> 00:39:58.350
These cares come off pretty easy.

759
00:39:58.350 --> 00:40:00.990
You can pull one out, look in the microscope

760
00:40:00.990 --> 00:40:04.050
and look for an exclamation point here.

761
00:40:04.050 --> 00:40:08.250
That is, it tends to be narrower at the proximal end

762
00:40:08.250 --> 00:40:12.063
and distally or it should be narrow, it tends to be bulbous.

763
00:40:13.050 --> 00:40:16.230
Sometimes you can see loss of scalp here completely,

764
00:40:16.230 --> 00:40:18.750
sometimes total loss of body hair,

765
00:40:18.750 --> 00:40:22.083
we call the last one, alopecia universalis.

766
00:40:23.070 --> 00:40:24.180
How do you treat this?

767
00:40:24.180 --> 00:40:27.720
Corticosteroids, injections or topical therapy,

768
00:40:27.720 --> 00:40:30.090
even systemic steroids.

769
00:40:30.090 --> 00:40:32.790
Topical minoxidil, neuro minoxidil.

770
00:40:32.790 --> 00:40:35.850
As a hypertensive agent, you can use it topically

771
00:40:35.850 --> 00:40:37.173
to grow hair on folks.

772
00:40:38.820 --> 00:40:41.910
Wigs do a good job in waiting for the patient to get better

773
00:40:41.910 --> 00:40:44.670
and most of them do within about a year,

774
00:40:44.670 --> 00:40:48.150
50% will have limited hair growth back.

775
00:40:48.150 --> 00:40:49.983
10% though may not.

776
00:40:51.180 --> 00:40:54.150
Pediculosis capitis.

777
00:40:54.150 --> 00:40:57.450
That's always of interest to us.

778
00:40:57.450 --> 00:41:00.240
Here we see the perpetrator, the Head Louse,

779
00:41:00.240 --> 00:41:02.490
posing for her prom picture.

780
00:41:02.490 --> 00:41:04.413
You're kinda cute, I think.

781
00:41:05.520 --> 00:41:07.470
How do you treat head louse?

782
00:41:07.470 --> 00:41:10.170
Pyrethroids are the first line agents,

783
00:41:10.170 --> 00:41:13.409
but there's resistance in some places to this.

784
00:41:13.409 --> 00:41:17.820
Malathion, benzoyl alcohol, topical ivermectin,

785
00:41:17.820 --> 00:41:21.150
even oral ivermectin, permethrin with Bactrim

786
00:41:21.150 --> 00:41:23.280
has been used for this.

787
00:41:23.280 --> 00:41:26.010
Important thing for us to know as family docs

788
00:41:26.010 --> 00:41:27.690
is children who have head lice

789
00:41:27.690 --> 00:41:30.780
once you start treatment, don't need to stay home.

790
00:41:30.780 --> 00:41:32.700
Even if they have some knits still present,

791
00:41:32.700 --> 00:41:36.150
they can go to school, they're not gonna affect anybody.

792
00:41:36.150 --> 00:41:39.300
But treat on the patient, treat close contacts,

793
00:41:39.300 --> 00:41:42.183
those who share bedding or in the same household.

794
00:41:43.020 --> 00:41:47.268
This is melasma, we have talked about hypopigmented lesions.

795
00:41:47.268 --> 00:41:50.340
Melasma is hyperpigmentation often associated

796
00:41:50.340 --> 00:41:52.983
with pregnancy called the mask of pregnancy.

797
00:41:55.140 --> 00:41:56.373
Case number seven.

798
00:42:00.900 --> 00:42:05.160
26-year-old male dermatology resident presented

799
00:42:05.160 --> 00:42:08.643
with your office about a new patch of warts on his penis.

800
00:42:10.320 --> 00:42:12.300
Funny that you should ask,

801
00:42:12.300 --> 00:42:16.230
my girlfriend has some of these umbilicated papules

802
00:42:16.230 --> 00:42:18.123
on her bottom as well.

803
00:42:20.610 --> 00:42:24.030
Most likely cause of this lesion is,

804
00:42:24.030 --> 00:42:27.570
treponema pallidum, herpes simplex,

805
00:42:27.570 --> 00:42:32.280
human papilloma virus or molluscum contagiosum virus.

806
00:42:32.280 --> 00:42:33.600
This one's a little hard.

807
00:42:33.600 --> 00:42:34.863
Let's see how you do.

808
00:42:38.995 --> 00:42:40.203
Molluscum contagiosum.

809
00:42:41.700 --> 00:42:44.343
What does our patient have? Molluscum Contagiosum.

810
00:42:47.040 --> 00:42:48.315
Oh, what's this?

811
00:42:48.315 --> 00:42:49.440
(attendees laughing)

812
00:42:49.440 --> 00:42:51.720
Well, going back to molluscum.

813
00:42:51.720 --> 00:42:53.940
No matter what the lesion looks like,

814
00:42:53.940 --> 00:42:55.740
if they say umbilicated papules,

815
00:42:55.740 --> 00:42:58.020
there's nothing else it could be, okay?

816
00:42:58.020 --> 00:42:59.550
This was a resident of mine

817
00:42:59.550 --> 00:43:01.920
when I was in Kentucky in Lexington.

818
00:43:01.920 --> 00:43:04.530
Went down to Destin, Florida for vacation,

819
00:43:04.530 --> 00:43:06.120
came back with this says,

820
00:43:06.120 --> 00:43:08.310
he has the largest genital wart in history,

821
00:43:08.310 --> 00:43:10.440
wants to take his picture for the Guinness Book of Records,

822
00:43:10.440 --> 00:43:11.730
which we did.

823
00:43:11.730 --> 00:43:13.200
And biopsy him too.

824
00:43:13.200 --> 00:43:14.670
Didn't hurt him.

825
00:43:14.670 --> 00:43:16.380
Pathologist calls back,

826
00:43:16.380 --> 00:43:19.590
plant fiber looking like cauliflower,

827
00:43:19.590 --> 00:43:22.890
so he didn't get sent into the Guinness Book of Records.

828
00:43:22.890 --> 00:43:26.700
But genital warts can look like cauliflower-like lesions.

829
00:43:26.700 --> 00:43:28.293
And this one is real.

830
00:43:30.090 --> 00:43:33.270
Warts are due to HPV infection, 150 types.

831
00:43:33.270 --> 00:43:37.947
Type one, plantar warts, type six and 11, genital warts.

832
00:43:37.947 --> 00:43:41.370
16, 18, 31, 33 are the bad actors

833
00:43:41.370 --> 00:43:42.993
that cause cervical cancer.

834
00:43:44.130 --> 00:43:46.470
How do you treat genital warts?

835
00:43:46.470 --> 00:43:49.050
Patients can treat 'em or we can treat 'em.

836
00:43:49.050 --> 00:43:52.334
Patient treatments include podofilox, imiquimod

837
00:43:52.334 --> 00:43:53.700
or sinecatechins.

838
00:43:53.700 --> 00:43:58.700
They're over a cycled treatment plant, also expensive.

839
00:43:59.130 --> 00:44:01.890
Or they come to us and we can freeze 'em,

840
00:44:01.890 --> 00:44:05.160
put acid on them or cut 'em out.

841
00:44:05.160 --> 00:44:08.400
We used to use something called Podophyllum resin

842
00:44:08.400 --> 00:44:11.553
and tincture of benzoin, smelled so good.

843
00:44:12.510 --> 00:44:15.030
CDC doesn't want us to use that anymore.

844
00:44:15.030 --> 00:44:17.160
They say it's too tissue toxic.

845
00:44:17.160 --> 00:44:18.780
But it was fun.

846
00:44:18.780 --> 00:44:20.523
The day went nicely after that.

847
00:44:21.480 --> 00:44:23.640
These are common warts.

848
00:44:23.640 --> 00:44:26.880
We teach residents that if you follow skin lines,

849
00:44:26.880 --> 00:44:29.913
the skin line will stop at the margin of the wart.

850
00:44:30.946 --> 00:44:34.838
If it's a callous, they'll usually go through the lesion

851
00:44:34.838 --> 00:44:38.100
and that's how you can tell a callous from a wart.

852
00:44:38.100 --> 00:44:41.100
Here's some more plantar warts, big ones.

853
00:44:41.100 --> 00:44:45.063
Here's a callous, actually ulcerating in a diabetic patient.

854
00:44:46.050 --> 00:44:49.050
But again, with callous skin line typically goes through,

855
00:44:49.050 --> 00:44:52.560
warts that typically stops at the lesion.

856
00:44:52.560 --> 00:44:55.413
Can you treat warts with duct tape?

857
00:44:56.370 --> 00:44:59.040
I don't know, but I would recommend if you do that,

858
00:44:59.040 --> 00:45:02.100
put a little bit of compound W under the duct tape,

859
00:45:02.100 --> 00:45:03.393
it might work better.

860
00:45:04.350 --> 00:45:06.450
This is genital herpes, again,

861
00:45:06.450 --> 00:45:09.210
it's our up with vesicles and ulcerate.

862
00:45:09.210 --> 00:45:12.390
Dr. Weismiller told us about how to treat that

863
00:45:12.390 --> 00:45:15.213
with acyclovir, famciclovir, and valacyclovir.

864
00:45:17.250 --> 00:45:19.833
This is molluscum, our patient has molluscum.

865
00:45:20.760 --> 00:45:25.500
Double-stranded DNA poxvirus, skin-to-skin inoculation.

866
00:45:25.500 --> 00:45:28.200
Children get it all over the place.

867
00:45:28.200 --> 00:45:30.840
If you see a child with it in the genital region

868
00:45:30.840 --> 00:45:34.410
and elsewhere, they're probably just self-inoculated.

869
00:45:34.410 --> 00:45:38.250
But if you see a child with only genital lesions,

870
00:45:38.250 --> 00:45:41.070
that would be somebody you worry about abuse.

871
00:45:41.070 --> 00:45:43.170
Adults have them in a genital area

872
00:45:43.170 --> 00:45:45.003
because it is sexually transmitted.

873
00:45:46.470 --> 00:45:47.760
How do you treat molluscum?

874
00:45:47.760 --> 00:45:49.200
You can leave 'em alone if you want,

875
00:45:49.200 --> 00:45:51.360
they'll go away eventually.

876
00:45:51.360 --> 00:45:52.530
But while they're there,

877
00:45:52.530 --> 00:45:55.680
then there's potential to spread it to others.

878
00:45:55.680 --> 00:45:57.900
You can trial them, you can correct 'em.

879
00:45:57.900 --> 00:46:00.270
Just don't do anything that's gonna really hurt the child

880
00:46:00.270 --> 00:46:02.460
or they won't come back to you for all the good medical care

881
00:46:02.460 --> 00:46:04.173
that you need to give them later.

882
00:46:07.530 --> 00:46:08.673
Case number eight.

883
00:46:09.720 --> 00:46:11.283
The case of the golden dome.

884
00:46:13.440 --> 00:46:16.530
68-year-old man sent in by his daughter concerned

885
00:46:16.530 --> 00:46:18.933
about a small growth on her father's scalp.

886
00:46:19.890 --> 00:46:22.530
Which of the followings most likely diagnosis?

887
00:46:22.530 --> 00:46:27.270
Keratoacanthoma, dermatofibroma, sebaceous hyperplasia

888
00:46:27.270 --> 00:46:29.163
or basal cell carcinoma?

889
00:46:34.440 --> 00:46:37.260
And you thought it's a basal cell, and that's right.

890
00:46:37.260 --> 00:46:39.210
Good job again, folks.

891
00:46:39.210 --> 00:46:41.790
This is a basal cell carcinoma.

892
00:46:41.790 --> 00:46:45.443
Modular lesions, basal cells, squamous cells,

893
00:46:45.443 --> 00:46:49.136
keratoacanthoma, sebaceous hyperplasia, melanomas,

894
00:46:49.136 --> 00:46:52.350
neurofibromas, they're all in there.

895
00:46:52.350 --> 00:46:54.810
This is sebaceous hyperplasia.

896
00:46:54.810 --> 00:46:57.591
Looks a little bit like what a basal cell might look like.

897
00:46:57.591 --> 00:46:59.190
It has some telangiectasias,

898
00:46:59.190 --> 00:47:01.290
but they're confined within the lobules.

899
00:47:01.290 --> 00:47:02.763
Usually these are multiple.

900
00:47:04.470 --> 00:47:07.204
Here's the keratoacanthoma.

901
00:47:07.204 --> 00:47:09.750
A looks like a volcano with keratin in it.

902
00:47:09.750 --> 00:47:11.970
There's a question of whether these are pre-malignant

903
00:47:11.970 --> 00:47:13.743
for squamous cell carcinoma.

904
00:47:15.450 --> 00:47:19.320
Basal cells are the most common skin cancer in men,

905
00:47:19.320 --> 00:47:21.780
often over age 40, 50.

906
00:47:21.780 --> 00:47:23.880
Often the head and neck region,

907
00:47:23.880 --> 00:47:25.980
they can stay small for many years

908
00:47:25.980 --> 00:47:28.590
and then all of a sudden kind of spurt.

909
00:47:28.590 --> 00:47:31.173
A diagnosis is by taking them off.

910
00:47:32.310 --> 00:47:34.470
Nodular basal cells are the most common,

911
00:47:34.470 --> 00:47:36.510
thankfully, the least aggressive.

912
00:47:36.510 --> 00:47:39.630
Superficial, sclerosing, pigmented basals

913
00:47:39.630 --> 00:47:42.060
and we'll see pictures of all of them.

914
00:47:42.060 --> 00:47:44.943
So here is a nodular basal cell.

915
00:47:46.800 --> 00:47:48.870
Here is another one more close up.

916
00:47:48.870 --> 00:47:52.473
Look at telangiectasias, not confined to within lobules.

917
00:47:54.360 --> 00:47:58.563
Another one eroding in front of the ear lobe.

918
00:48:00.270 --> 00:48:01.953
Here's one that's superficial.

919
00:48:03.000 --> 00:48:06.393
Here's the one that's sclerosis or scar-like basal cell.

920
00:48:08.070 --> 00:48:10.770
The treatment is by eliminating them.

921
00:48:10.770 --> 00:48:13.290
Excisional biopsies are often adequate.

922
00:48:13.290 --> 00:48:16.263
You can correct them or cryo them if they're small.

923
00:48:19.530 --> 00:48:21.810
If you're dealing with a larger lesion

924
00:48:21.810 --> 00:48:25.290
or in a high recurrence area like the nose or the eye,

925
00:48:25.290 --> 00:48:28.443
the margins are not clear, they're large again,

926
00:48:29.370 --> 00:48:31.410
we have to worry about conserving tissue,

927
00:48:31.410 --> 00:48:35.493
then send them to Mohs for Mohs micrographic surgery.

928
00:48:37.290 --> 00:48:40.590
Radiation therapy can be used for non-surgical candidates.

929
00:48:40.590 --> 00:48:42.570
Imiquimod, 5-FU.

930
00:48:42.570 --> 00:48:45.230
And there's even a medicine, vismodegib

931
00:48:46.200 --> 00:48:49.080
that can be used for metastatic basal cells.

932
00:48:49.080 --> 00:48:50.073
That's fairly new.

933
00:48:51.210 --> 00:48:52.923
Actinic keratosis.

934
00:48:54.480 --> 00:48:57.360
Here we see a man with multiple AKs.

935
00:48:57.360 --> 00:48:59.010
Oftentimes you can feel these

936
00:48:59.010 --> 00:49:00.573
before you can even see them.

937
00:49:01.800 --> 00:49:03.150
More often in the elderly,

938
00:49:03.150 --> 00:49:06.900
fair-skinned individuals on sun-exposed areas.

939
00:49:06.900 --> 00:49:10.020
So the head, neck, forearms, hands behind the ears,

940
00:49:10.020 --> 00:49:11.343
look behind the ear lobes.

941
00:49:12.180 --> 00:49:15.690
Rough scaly patches, small, multiple,

942
00:49:15.690 --> 00:49:19.080
usually don't hurt, usually don't itch.

943
00:49:19.080 --> 00:49:21.090
But why do we worry about 'em?

944
00:49:21.090 --> 00:49:22.620
And because they're pre-malignant,

945
00:49:22.620 --> 00:49:25.020
they turn into squamous cell carcinomas.

946
00:49:25.020 --> 00:49:29.583
Not all of them do, certainly, but we worry about 'em.

947
00:49:30.420 --> 00:49:31.770
How do we treat 'em?

948
00:49:31.770 --> 00:49:33.720
Freeze 'em, that's a lot of fun to freeze 'em

949
00:49:33.720 --> 00:49:37.143
or curate 'em, or laser them if you have a laser machine.

950
00:49:39.480 --> 00:49:41.640
Or you can give the patient a prescription

951
00:49:41.640 --> 00:49:46.640
for topical 5-FU, imiquimod, even diclofenac gel,

952
00:49:46.830 --> 00:49:51.180
ingenol or the new ones, tirbanibulin,

953
00:49:51.180 --> 00:49:52.680
can't pronounce that.

954
00:49:52.680 --> 00:49:54.840
Again, tend to be expensive agents

955
00:49:54.840 --> 00:49:56.520
and they'll apply them readily

956
00:49:56.520 --> 00:49:59.130
and then the lesions hopefully resolved.

957
00:49:59.130 --> 00:50:02.763
Bowen's disease, again, squamous cell carcinoma in situ.

958
00:50:03.840 --> 00:50:07.143
Here's a keratoacanthoma again, looks like a volcano.

959
00:50:08.010 --> 00:50:10.380
And here's a squamous cell carcinoma.

960
00:50:10.380 --> 00:50:12.750
The big kahuna himself.

961
00:50:12.750 --> 00:50:16.410
Precursors, again, AKs, maybe keratoacanthomas,

962
00:50:16.410 --> 00:50:19.500
cutaneous horns, Bowen's disease.

963
00:50:19.500 --> 00:50:24.030
They occur on disease or injured skin with radiation

964
00:50:24.030 --> 00:50:26.850
or immunosuppression, they tend to blossom.

965
00:50:26.850 --> 00:50:29.340
I have a patient who has a liver transplant

966
00:50:29.340 --> 00:50:32.190
on immunosuppressants and keeps on popping up with these.

967
00:50:33.210 --> 00:50:36.000
You diagnose them if you want, by a shave technique

968
00:50:36.000 --> 00:50:37.980
or a punch biopsy.

969
00:50:37.980 --> 00:50:41.100
And then the surgical excision is the treatment of choice.

970
00:50:41.100 --> 00:50:43.230
If they're small, cryotherapy

971
00:50:43.230 --> 00:50:46.470
or electrodesiccation/curettage will work,

972
00:50:46.470 --> 00:50:48.963
radiation in difficult to treat areas.

973
00:50:51.720 --> 00:50:53.970
Case number nine, we're getting through this.

974
00:50:54.840 --> 00:50:57.723
Look at these, case number nine, lesions.

975
00:51:00.090 --> 00:51:03.690
55-year-old man found to have these skin lesions

976
00:51:03.690 --> 00:51:05.970
at the time of a routine exam,

977
00:51:05.970 --> 00:51:08.320
has a lot more than just these two, by the way.

978
00:51:11.850 --> 00:51:12.683
Which of the following

979
00:51:12.683 --> 00:51:15.480
would be most reasonable course of action?

980
00:51:15.480 --> 00:51:19.860
Treatment with topical 5-FU, observing these lesions,

981
00:51:19.860 --> 00:51:23.670
excisional biopsy with wide four centimeter margins

982
00:51:23.670 --> 00:51:26.343
or referral for Mohs micrographic surgery?

983
00:51:31.110 --> 00:51:33.630
And you're gonna observe them, good.

984
00:51:33.630 --> 00:51:35.823
Why? What's this person have?

985
00:51:38.315 --> 00:51:40.050
Seborrheic keratoses,

986
00:51:40.050 --> 00:51:42.303
old age barnacles as we used to call them.

987
00:51:47.040 --> 00:51:48.870
These are pigmented lesions,

988
00:51:48.870 --> 00:51:53.130
intradermal nevus, melanomas, SKs, Kaposi's sarcoma,

989
00:51:53.130 --> 00:51:57.303
cherry angiomas, pigmented basals or pigmented lesions.

990
00:51:58.230 --> 00:52:01.800
Here we see a cherry angioma, very characteristic.

991
00:52:01.800 --> 00:52:04.170
If we see a patient come to clinic or in the hospital,

992
00:52:04.170 --> 00:52:07.200
we take all the medical students and show them this,

993
00:52:07.200 --> 00:52:09.480
so they can at least diagnose one skin condition

994
00:52:09.480 --> 00:52:10.780
by the time they graduate.

995
00:52:12.120 --> 00:52:13.740
Hemangiomas.

996
00:52:13.740 --> 00:52:17.250
See these often, they tend to bleed readily.

997
00:52:17.250 --> 00:52:19.410
So do these pyrogenic granulomas,

998
00:52:19.410 --> 00:52:22.350
don't get into one of these unless you're prepared.

999
00:52:22.350 --> 00:52:24.060
They tend to bleed.

1000
00:52:24.060 --> 00:52:27.420
This is an atypical dysplastic nevus.

1001
00:52:27.420 --> 00:52:28.893
Look at it carefully.

1002
00:52:31.080 --> 00:52:34.380
Here's a malignant melanoma, look at it carefully.

1003
00:52:34.380 --> 00:52:36.150
Looks a lot alike.

1004
00:52:36.150 --> 00:52:37.800
And that's our problem

1005
00:52:37.800 --> 00:52:40.830
is trying to differentiate the two of those.

1006
00:52:40.830 --> 00:52:43.970
You're probably not gonna miss this melanoma,

1007
00:52:43.970 --> 00:52:46.773
the nodular component there on the left, particularly.

1008
00:52:47.820 --> 00:52:51.300
Who gets melanomas? Non-Hispanic Caucasians

1009
00:52:51.300 --> 00:52:55.200
in their 50s and 60s, men more than women.

1010
00:52:55.200 --> 00:52:56.250
Problem with these things

1011
00:52:56.250 --> 00:52:59.730
is that they metastasize early and widely.

1012
00:52:59.730 --> 00:53:01.440
Thankfully, a lot better treatments now

1013
00:53:01.440 --> 00:53:03.330
than we didn't have before.

1014
00:53:03.330 --> 00:53:05.610
So who's at risk for melanoma?

1015
00:53:05.610 --> 00:53:08.760
Large number of atypicals, other skin cancers.

1016
00:53:08.760 --> 00:53:12.090
Congenital giant nevus, a family history,

1017
00:53:12.090 --> 00:53:15.003
immunosuppressed, radiation exposures.

1018
00:53:15.960 --> 00:53:18.360
There are different melanoma subtypes.

1019
00:53:18.360 --> 00:53:21.090
Superficial spreading is most common.

1020
00:53:21.090 --> 00:53:26.010
There are nodular, lentigo and acral lentiginous melanomas.

1021
00:53:26.010 --> 00:53:27.423
And we'll see some pictures.

1022
00:53:28.620 --> 00:53:31.200
What to look out for in diagnosing a melanoma?

1023
00:53:31.200 --> 00:53:35.700
Remember the A-B-C-D-U of melanoma.

1024
00:53:35.700 --> 00:53:37.680
Lesions that are asymmetrical.

1025
00:53:37.680 --> 00:53:40.620
The border is irregular, not well-defined.

1026
00:53:40.620 --> 00:53:43.020
Color is variable.

1027
00:53:43.020 --> 00:53:45.210
Diameter of over six millimeters,

1028
00:53:45.210 --> 00:53:47.373
the lesions changing over time,

1029
00:53:47.373 --> 00:53:50.040
what they call the ugly duckling sign.

1030
00:53:50.040 --> 00:53:52.590
This one looks different than the others

1031
00:53:52.590 --> 00:53:54.300
on the same patient.

1032
00:53:54.300 --> 00:53:56.193
So look out for that one.

1033
00:53:57.060 --> 00:53:59.463
Here's a superficial spreading melanoma,

1034
00:54:01.073 --> 00:54:03.363
a nodular malignant melanoma,

1035
00:54:04.405 --> 00:54:07.920
a lentigo maligna, these are again,

1036
00:54:07.920 --> 00:54:10.833
lesions that are macular rather than papular/nodular.

1037
00:54:12.095 --> 00:54:15.840
Acral lentiginous in the nail itself.

1038
00:54:15.840 --> 00:54:17.073
Look out for those.

1039
00:54:18.510 --> 00:54:20.910
What are some characteristics of that?

1040
00:54:20.910 --> 00:54:24.300
Older patient, dark color to that streak.

1041
00:54:24.300 --> 00:54:29.300
One nail involved, not multiple, wide, irregular margins

1042
00:54:29.910 --> 00:54:34.140
and pigmentation in the periungual area.

1043
00:54:34.140 --> 00:54:37.350
I have a number of patients, African Americans

1044
00:54:37.350 --> 00:54:40.470
who have multiple vertical streaks.

1045
00:54:40.470 --> 00:54:41.940
That's normal for them.

1046
00:54:41.940 --> 00:54:45.600
But if you see one guy or one patient, just one of them,

1047
00:54:45.600 --> 00:54:48.570
and it's regular at that male margin, boom,

1048
00:54:48.570 --> 00:54:53.100
that's not normal and if you biopsy and treat it.

1049
00:54:53.100 --> 00:54:55.980
With melanoma, the thickness determines prognosis.

1050
00:54:55.980 --> 00:54:59.670
So any biopsy you do needs to be full thickness

1051
00:54:59.670 --> 00:55:01.440
for diagnosis.

1052
00:55:01.440 --> 00:55:06.333
The more thicker it is, the more worse the prognosis.

1053
00:55:07.920 --> 00:55:11.310
Treatment for melanoma is a wide local excision.

1054
00:55:11.310 --> 00:55:12.720
Doesn't have to be four centimeters,

1055
00:55:12.720 --> 00:55:16.020
you don't have to create a crater in that patient.

1056
00:55:16.020 --> 00:55:20.040
Usually four millimeters is typically wide enough,

1057
00:55:20.040 --> 00:55:24.000
but you want to also look at the sentinel node in that area.

1058
00:55:24.000 --> 00:55:26.850
And immunotherapy rather than chemotherapy

1059
00:55:26.850 --> 00:55:28.653
is the way to go now for melanoma.

1060
00:55:29.550 --> 00:55:33.930
These are SKs like our patient has, numerous ones.

1061
00:55:33.930 --> 00:55:36.480
And if you're gonna biopsy one worrying about a melanoma,

1062
00:55:36.480 --> 00:55:37.803
do it full thickness.

1063
00:55:39.210 --> 00:55:41.310
You can punch it if you need to.

1064
00:55:41.310 --> 00:55:42.690
If you're certain it's an SK,

1065
00:55:42.690 --> 00:55:44.970
you can leave it alone and watch 'em

1066
00:55:44.970 --> 00:55:48.273
or you can use cryotherapy, or curettage on them.

1067
00:55:49.590 --> 00:55:54.090
The board may ask you about the sign of Leser-trelat,

1068
00:55:54.090 --> 00:55:55.890
it has in the past.

1069
00:55:55.890 --> 00:55:59.310
This is a patient all of a sudden develops all these SKs

1070
00:55:59.310 --> 00:56:00.303
for no reason.

1071
00:56:01.440 --> 00:56:04.140
This tends to be associated with internal malignancies,

1072
00:56:04.140 --> 00:56:06.360
particularly the GI tract,

1073
00:56:06.360 --> 00:56:08.643
particularly adenocarcinoma of the stomach.

1074
00:56:09.600 --> 00:56:13.920
So be wary of the sign of Leser-trelat.

1075
00:56:13.920 --> 00:56:16.410
This is dermatosis papulosa nigra,

1076
00:56:16.410 --> 00:56:19.140
an SK variant on the skin.

1077
00:56:19.140 --> 00:56:21.120
Don't be too aggressive in treating these

1078
00:56:21.120 --> 00:56:23.580
and cause scars in your patient.

1079
00:56:23.580 --> 00:56:26.433
Skin tags are another SK variant.

1080
00:56:27.630 --> 00:56:30.630
Our last case, case number 10.

1081
00:56:30.630 --> 00:56:31.480
Can you see this?

1082
00:56:35.010 --> 00:56:38.310
39-year-old woman complained of a lump on her back,

1083
00:56:38.310 --> 00:56:41.550
gotten bigger and smaller over the past several years,

1084
00:56:41.550 --> 00:56:44.583
occasionally some cheesy-looking material.

1085
00:56:49.230 --> 00:56:52.020
So you tell her that the material within the lesion

1086
00:56:52.020 --> 00:56:54.183
is most likely which of the following?

1087
00:56:55.050 --> 00:56:56.580
If you get this right,

1088
00:56:56.580 --> 00:57:00.420
you've gotten all 10 of these questions right.

1089
00:57:00.420 --> 00:57:03.963
No group has ever gotten 10 of these questions right.

1090
00:57:04.920 --> 00:57:09.630
So the most likely thing within that lesion is the keratin,

1091
00:57:09.630 --> 00:57:13.233
is it sebum, is it pus or is it cheese?

1092
00:57:20.040 --> 00:57:22.556
Oh, the late voters took over this election.

1093
00:57:22.556 --> 00:57:23.610
(attendees laughing)

1094
00:57:23.610 --> 00:57:25.230
Good for you.

1095
00:57:25.230 --> 00:57:26.787
It's keratin.

1096
00:57:26.787 --> 00:57:28.740
It's not sebum, it's certainly is not cheese,

1097
00:57:28.740 --> 00:57:30.243
even if you're from Wisconsin.

1098
00:57:31.680 --> 00:57:33.393
These are epidermal cysts.

1099
00:57:34.470 --> 00:57:39.470
We also call them sebaceous cysts, epidural cysts,

1100
00:57:39.690 --> 00:57:42.270
or epidermal inclusion cyst.

1101
00:57:42.270 --> 00:57:44.940
Most in common kinda cyst we see,

1102
00:57:44.940 --> 00:57:46.980
they have that central punctum,

1103
00:57:46.980 --> 00:57:49.080
that's how you can identify them.

1104
00:57:49.080 --> 00:57:52.050
The cyst wall produces keratin, not sebum,

1105
00:57:52.050 --> 00:57:55.560
the keratin is greasy and smelly, it's sebum.

1106
00:57:55.560 --> 00:57:58.320
Some of these things will rupture spontaneously

1107
00:57:58.320 --> 00:58:01.290
or they can become inflamed spontaneously.

1108
00:58:01.290 --> 00:58:04.110
If they're inflamed and they're uninfected,

1109
00:58:04.110 --> 00:58:07.200
then we don't treat them and choosing wisely suggest,

1110
00:58:07.200 --> 00:58:11.220
don't use antibiotics if they're inflamed, but not infected.

1111
00:58:11.220 --> 00:58:15.750
You can inject triamcinolone, as hasten resolution.

1112
00:58:15.750 --> 00:58:18.723
Excision is best done when they're not inflamed.

1113
00:58:19.590 --> 00:58:21.450
If they're infected and fluctuant

1114
00:58:21.450 --> 00:58:23.580
then, of course, you're gonna drain them

1115
00:58:23.580 --> 00:58:26.313
and use antibiotics if they're surrounding cellulitis.

1116
00:58:27.960 --> 00:58:29.940
And those antibiotics you might use are those

1117
00:58:29.940 --> 00:58:32.553
that you use to treat staph and strep infections.

1118
00:58:33.840 --> 00:58:35.580
This is a lipoma.

1119
00:58:35.580 --> 00:58:37.650
Nobody's gonna miss this one.

1120
00:58:37.650 --> 00:58:40.620
This is a keloid, a nasty looking keloid.

1121
00:58:40.620 --> 00:58:43.290
Keloids are hypertrophic scars.

1122
00:58:43.290 --> 00:58:45.990
We can treat them with intralesional steroids

1123
00:58:45.990 --> 00:58:47.250
with improvement,

1124
00:58:47.250 --> 00:58:49.380
but it's hard to inject the steroid in.

1125
00:58:49.380 --> 00:58:51.180
Takes a little bit of work for those

1126
00:58:51.180 --> 00:58:53.760
and it takes multiple injections over time

1127
00:58:53.760 --> 00:58:54.843
to make a difference.

1128
00:58:55.980 --> 00:59:00.593
This is a neurofibroma, also look for cafe au lait spots.

1129
00:59:01.500 --> 00:59:03.393
This is a hereditary problem.

1130
00:59:04.650 --> 00:59:07.110
And xanthelasmas, you can see them in the corner

1131
00:59:07.110 --> 00:59:09.360
of the eyes, lipid deposits,

1132
00:59:09.360 --> 00:59:13.560
they don't always associated with a hyperlipidemia

1133
00:59:13.560 --> 00:59:14.850
and they don't always get better

1134
00:59:14.850 --> 00:59:17.670
if you treat them with things like Lipitor.

1135
00:59:17.670 --> 00:59:21.840
So that's it for your run through dermatology.

1136
00:59:21.840 --> 00:59:24.504
<v Announcer>Thank you very much, Dr. Levine.</v>

1137
00:59:24.504 --> 00:59:27.087
(bright music)

